 Jennings &lt;shentino&#64;gmail.com&gt; wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; I am curious about what's supposed to happen normally on signal delivery.<br />&gt;<br />&gt; Is SS a register that's supposed to be preserved like EIP/RIP and CS when a<br />&gt; signal is delivered?<br /><br />What exactly does "supposed" mean?<br /><br />On x86-64, we traditionally haven't touched SS, because it doesn't<br />really matter in 64-bit long mode. And apparently dosemu depended on<br />that behavior.<br /><br />So clearly, we're not "supposed" to save/restore it. Because reality<br />matters a hell of a lot more than any theoretical arguments.<br /><br />                Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
